1
00:00:26,826 --> 00:00:29,062
(MELLOW TUNE PLAYING ON PIANO)

2
00:00:52,919 --> 00:00:54,654
What happened?

3
00:00:54,687 --> 00:00:57,123
Emma fell down again
   riding that bike.

4
00:00:57,157 --> 00:00:59,459
She just won't quit
   on that thing, will she?

5
00:00:59,492 --> 00:01:01,394
I can't imagine
 where she gets her
 stubborn streak from.

6
00:01:01,428 --> 00:01:02,896
(CHUCKLES)

7
00:01:02,929 --> 00:01:04,798
She probably
wouldn't fall if you
gave her a few lessons.

8
00:01:04,831 --> 00:01:06,232
I will.

9
00:01:06,266 --> 00:01:08,868
As soon as I get back.

10
00:01:08,902 --> 00:01:12,705
Sebastian, you've
 been saying that
 since Emma was born.

11
00:01:12,739 --> 00:01:14,507
-Ow! Damn!
   -(HISSES)

12
00:01:14,541 --> 00:01:16,142
Here. Put your head down.

13
00:01:18,378 --> 00:01:20,613
-Man!
   -Sebastian, it's
   just some blood.

14
00:01:20,647 --> 00:01:23,216
I hate the sight of blood.

15
00:01:23,249 --> 00:01:24,884
You mean you hate the
   sight of your own blood.

16
00:01:24,918 --> 00:01:26,686
(BOTH LAUGH)

17
00:01:26,719 --> 00:01:28,788
This is it, Karen.

18
00:01:28,822 --> 00:01:32,826
A couple of weeks from now,
I'm out of the
systems business.

19
00:01:32,859 --> 00:01:35,795
You've also been saying
   that since Emma was born.

20
00:01:43,403 --> 00:01:45,305
You be good like I asked you,

21
00:01:45,338 --> 00:01:47,207
and I'll bring you back
   something special, okay?

22
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:48,641
When are you
  coming back, Daddy?

23
00:01:48,675 --> 00:01:50,276
In about a week.

24
00:01:50,310 --> 00:01:51,544
And I want you to
   be good for Mommy, okay?

25
00:01:51,578 --> 00:01:52,679
-Okay.
  -All right.

26
00:01:52,712 --> 00:01:54,614
Take care of my baby,
  Mr. Paws.

27
00:01:54,647 --> 00:01:55,815
I love you, pumpkin.

28
00:01:55,849 --> 00:01:56,916
I love you, Daddy.

29
00:01:56,950 --> 00:01:58,485
-Wanna walk me to the car?
 -Okay.

30
00:02:01,721 --> 00:02:03,456
See you in a week.

31
00:02:03,490 --> 00:02:05,458
We are gonna make this work,
   aren't we?

32
00:02:05,492 --> 00:02:08,728
We are. Last trip, I promise.

33
00:02:08,761 --> 00:02:11,364
-I love you.
   -Me too.

34
00:02:11,397 --> 00:02:12,732
Be careful.

35
00:02:12,765 --> 00:02:14,467
-Oh, yeah.
   -(ENGINE STARTS)

36
00:02:14,501 --> 00:02:16,236
Computer conferences
can be deadly.

37
00:02:17,370 --> 00:02:18,404
(HANDBRAKE RELEASES)

38
00:02:18,438 --> 00:02:19,572
-Bye.
 -Bye.

39
00:02:41,561 --> 00:02:43,863
(AIRPLANE FLYING OVERHEAD)

40
00:03:32,745 --> 00:03:33,913
-Good morning.
-Hola.

41
00:03:35,782 --> 00:03:38,251
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

42
00:03:40,954 --> 00:03:44,924
-Good. And the equipment?
  -My meeting has been arranged
  for tonight.

43
00:03:57,570 --> 00:03:59,339
(ENGINE STARTS)

44
00:04:17,123 --> 00:04:18,591
(INAUDIBLE)

45
00:04:22,962 --> 00:04:23,997
Gracias.

46
00:04:41,147 --> 00:04:43,683
(HUMMING)

47
00:05:07,774 --> 00:05:10,643
The wick will burn
for one minute.

48
00:05:10,677 --> 00:05:13,379
When the wick goes out,
 you have 20 seconds.

49
00:05:15,581 --> 00:05:18,017
And, Dellacourt,

50
00:05:18,051 --> 00:05:20,653
when this goes off,
  be somewhere else.

51
00:06:07,567 --> 00:06:11,671
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

52
00:06:51,978 --> 00:06:53,079
AMBASSADOR:
  Robert, I told you.

53
00:06:53,112 --> 00:06:56,616
I have financial and political
 commitments of my own.

54
00:06:56,649 --> 00:06:59,051
Well, Ambassador,
  the government's
  lack of enthusiasm

55
00:06:59,085 --> 00:07:01,888
for the President's position
   has him concerned.

56
00:07:01,921 --> 00:07:03,756
Your role in the UN
 is an important one.

57
00:07:03,790 --> 00:07:05,191
Especially in an
election year.

58
00:07:05,224 --> 00:07:07,527
Ah. A little to the right
  of the center

59
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:10,897
for your bleeding hearts,
 I suspect. (CHUCKLES)

60
00:07:10,930 --> 00:07:13,065
This could get you into
the big game.

61
00:07:13,099 --> 00:07:15,601
All right.
 Contact your people.
 We will have a word.

62
00:07:15,635 --> 00:07:18,571
But later. It is, after all,
   my birthday!

63
00:07:18,604 --> 00:07:20,072
(ALL CHEERING)

64
00:07:28,881 --> 00:07:30,216
Elizabeth, where's
 your husband?

65
00:07:30,249 --> 00:07:32,084
On second thought,
  I'm glad you're here alone.

66
00:07:32,118 --> 00:07:33,619
And as lovely as ever.

67
00:07:33,653 --> 00:07:35,888
(GREETING IN SPANISH)

68
00:07:46,699 --> 00:07:48,100
AMBASSADOR: I wish to thank
my many friends

69
00:07:48,134 --> 00:07:49,969
in the American
 diplomatic community

70
00:07:50,002 --> 00:07:52,038
for such an extravagant
reminder

71
00:07:52,071 --> 00:07:53,573
of my impending old age.

72
00:07:53,606 --> 00:07:55,174
(ALL LAUGH)

73
00:07:55,208 --> 00:07:58,678
I shall never forgive you.
 (CHUCKLES)

74
00:07:58,711 --> 00:08:01,047
The people of our country
  share a great deal

75
00:08:01,080 --> 00:08:03,015
with the people
 in your own country.

76
00:08:03,049 --> 00:08:06,185
We both value family
 and friends,

77
00:08:06,219 --> 00:08:09,288
we strive to develop
   new opportunities

78
00:08:09,322 --> 00:08:11,591
for ourselves
   and our citizens.

79
00:08:11,624 --> 00:08:16,329
We both value a strong
  and stable world community

80
00:08:16,362 --> 00:08:18,130
with continued
   economic growth,

81
00:08:18,164 --> 00:08:20,199
free from the heavy hand
   of government.

82
00:08:20,233 --> 00:08:21,133
(ALL APPLAUDING)

83
00:08:23,736 --> 00:08:25,771
Today, the hand of government

84
00:08:25,805 --> 00:08:28,708
weighs heavily
   on the shoulders
   of our citizens.

85
00:08:28,741 --> 00:08:31,244
And the hand of crime
   waves more weapons

86
00:08:31,277 --> 00:08:34,013
in the face of the
 innocent and the unprotected.

87
00:08:34,780 --> 00:08:36,682
We live in a time

88
00:08:36,716 --> 00:08:39,919
where we must marshal
   our own support,

89
00:08:39,952 --> 00:08:42,755
to bring our own resources
   to bear upon the problem.

90
00:08:42,788 --> 00:08:45,358
(ALL APPLAUDING)

91
00:08:45,391 --> 00:08:47,793
AMBASSADOR: We must
   act responsibly,

92
00:08:47,827 --> 00:08:49,028
but we must act.

93
00:08:50,296 --> 00:08:52,665
The people in my country

94
00:08:52,698 --> 00:08:56,269
want your country to again
 be the example
 it once was.

95
00:08:56,302 --> 00:08:58,104
We want you to emerge

96
00:08:58,137 --> 00:09:02,041
from the upcoming election
 as the conscience
 of the free world.

97
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:07,013
But,

98
00:09:07,046 --> 00:09:08,915
this is a
 birthday celebration,

99
00:09:08,948 --> 00:09:10,716
a happy occasion.

100
00:09:10,750 --> 00:09:13,886
So, my birthday present
to you is

101
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:17,657
my commitment
to support that effort
in any way that I can.

102
00:09:17,690 --> 00:09:19,225
(ALL CHEERING)

103
00:09:28,968 --> 00:09:30,703
(PEOPLE EXCLAIMING)

104
00:09:40,112 --> 00:09:42,682
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

105
00:09:42,715 --> 00:09:44,817
Oh, thank you. Beautiful.

106
00:09:44,850 --> 00:09:45,985
Make the last wish.

107
00:09:51,457 --> 00:09:53,159
I would like to make a wish

108
00:09:53,192 --> 00:09:55,227
for the future
  of a strong Chile.

109
00:09:57,196 --> 00:09:58,831
(ALL CHEERING)

110
00:10:19,819 --> 00:10:21,120
-MAN: It's a bomb!
   -(ALL SCREAMING)

111
00:10:22,054 --> 00:10:23,089
(GRUNTS)

112
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:55,488
(PEOPLE SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

113
00:10:55,521 --> 00:10:57,123
(SHOUTING IN SPANISH)

114
00:10:59,992 --> 00:11:01,093
(GUNSHOT)

115
00:11:01,127 --> 00:11:02,261
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

116
00:11:02,294 --> 00:11:03,095
(GUNSHOTS FIRING)

117
00:11:18,811 --> 00:11:20,012
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

118
00:13:01,881 --> 00:13:02,915
(GRUNTS)

119
00:13:14,026 --> 00:13:15,161
(GRUNTING)

120
00:14:02,208 --> 00:14:04,143
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

121
00:14:26,498 --> 00:14:28,300
(AIRPLANE FLYING OVERHEAD)

122
00:14:35,641 --> 00:14:37,710
(TIRES SCREECHING)

123
00:14:37,743 --> 00:14:41,013
Freeze! Federal agents!
Hands in the air!
Hold it!

124
00:14:41,046 --> 00:14:43,449
Freeze! Federal agent!

125
00:14:43,482 --> 00:14:45,184
Put up your hands!
  Get 'em up!

126
00:14:45,217 --> 00:14:46,986
(DISTORTED SHOUTING)

127
00:14:50,489 --> 00:14:52,057
MAN: (DISTORTED) No! No!

128
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:53,626
(GUN FIRING)

129
00:15:44,243 --> 00:15:46,045
(WHISPERING) Oh, God.

130
00:15:48,080 --> 00:15:50,082
I'm so sorry.

131
00:15:50,115 --> 00:15:51,583
KAREN: 
You lied
   about all of it.

132
00:15:53,152 --> 00:15:54,353
You kill people.

133
00:15:56,355 --> 00:15:57,723
For the government, Karen.

134
00:15:57,756 --> 00:16:00,559
For the United States
  Government.

135
00:16:00,592 --> 00:16:02,127
That's not what they say.

136
00:16:02,161 --> 00:16:05,297
For God's sakes,
what did you think
they would say?

137
00:16:05,331 --> 00:16:06,298
(WHISPERING) How could you?

138
00:16:07,199 --> 00:16:08,767
How could you lie?

139
00:16:08,801 --> 00:16:11,704
How could you kill?
 How could you do this to us?

140
00:16:11,737 --> 00:16:14,707
I didn't do this to us.
  I did this for us.

141
00:16:14,740 --> 00:16:16,542
I'm a soldier.

142
00:16:16,575 --> 00:16:18,043
When I came back
   from the service,

143
00:16:18,077 --> 00:16:19,545
they offered me
an opportunity.

144
00:16:19,578 --> 00:16:21,747
-An "opportunity"?
-Please don't.

145
00:16:21,780 --> 00:16:23,716
An opportunity for what?
 To become a murderer?

146
00:16:23,749 --> 00:16:24,683
Please.
   I don't know what to say.

147
00:16:24,717 --> 00:16:26,318
What were you gonna do
  for career advance?

148
00:16:26,352 --> 00:16:26,785
Become a serial killer,
 then a mass murderer?

149
00:16:28,620 --> 00:16:30,723
Now Mr. Dellacourt,

150
00:16:30,756 --> 00:16:33,592
why would the
  US Government want to kill
  one of its own ambassadors?

151
00:16:35,094 --> 00:16:37,129
I was briefed he was
an arms dealer.

152
00:16:37,162 --> 00:16:41,367
Preparing to sell stolen
US military supplies
to one of our enemies.

153
00:16:41,400 --> 00:16:44,169
CIA operatives in the field
  couldn't get close to him.

154
00:16:44,203 --> 00:16:45,637
Apparently I was
a last resort,

155
00:16:45,671 --> 00:16:48,407
but I never fulfilled
 the contract.

156
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:50,175
You never fulfilled
 the contract?

157
00:16:50,209 --> 00:16:52,111
I didn't kill the Ambassador.

158
00:16:52,144 --> 00:16:53,746
I aborted the mission.

159
00:16:53,779 --> 00:16:55,414
Someone else killed him.

160
00:16:55,447 --> 00:16:58,283
So you've said, repeatedly.

161
00:16:58,317 --> 00:17:01,153
But the Ambassador
  is definitely dead.

162
00:17:01,186 --> 00:17:04,523
And by your own admission,
 you accepted the assignment.

163
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:08,460
Who was the man
   who led this operation,
   who gave you your orders?

164
00:17:08,494 --> 00:17:10,062
You know I can't
   tell you that, Counselor.

165
00:17:11,363 --> 00:17:13,198
Why not?

166
00:17:13,232 --> 00:17:15,501
Because my life and my family
  would be in jeopardy.

167
00:17:15,534 --> 00:17:17,536
I simply can't tell you.

168
00:17:17,569 --> 00:17:18,404
Ah.

169
00:17:20,339 --> 00:17:22,341
Now, Mr. Dellacourt,
 you are aware

170
00:17:22,374 --> 00:17:24,109
that the Central
  Intelligence Agency

171
00:17:24,143 --> 00:17:25,744
has absolutely no record
  of your employment

172
00:17:25,778 --> 00:17:28,447
or involvement with them ever.

173
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:29,615
They don't even know
 who you are.

174
00:17:29,648 --> 00:17:32,785
Of course I'm aware that
 that's what you would be told.

175
00:17:32,818 --> 00:17:34,319
What else could they tell you?

176
00:17:34,353 --> 00:17:37,790
It's the only thing
 they would tell you.

177
00:17:37,823 --> 00:17:40,726
Ambassador Ramirez was not an
 arms dealer, Mr. Dellacourt.

178
00:17:40,759 --> 00:17:43,595
In fact, very far from it.

179
00:17:43,629 --> 00:17:47,266
He chaired the UN Council
  on international terrorism.

180
00:17:47,299 --> 00:17:50,369
And was a close advisor
 to our own President.

181
00:17:50,402 --> 00:17:52,871
FEMALE REPORTER:
 Sebastian Dellacourt was
 sentenced here today

182
00:17:52,905 --> 00:17:55,174
at Federal District Court
 for the assassination

183
00:17:55,207 --> 00:17:58,677
of Enrique Ramirez,
 Chilean Ambassador to the US.

184
00:17:58,710 --> 00:18:00,846
Dellacourt will serve
a life sentence

185
00:18:00,879 --> 00:18:05,217
without possibility of parole
 in a maximum security prison.

186
00:18:05,250 --> 00:18:07,152
KAREN: 
It's been three years
  and two appeals.

187
00:18:08,420 --> 00:18:09,688
I need to move on.

188
00:18:10,656 --> 00:18:12,524
Emma needs to move on.

189
00:18:13,625 --> 00:18:14,726
I don't know you anymore.

190
00:18:16,628 --> 00:18:19,398
I'm not sure we ever did.
 You led a life apart from us.

191
00:18:20,499 --> 00:18:21,767
A dangerous, cruel life.

192
00:18:24,269 --> 00:18:25,804
You're a stranger, Sebastian.

193
00:18:27,473 --> 00:18:29,308
There is a part of you
  that is very ugly.

194
00:18:29,341 --> 00:18:30,876
-Karen, if you just...
 -No, listen.

195
00:18:34,947 --> 00:18:37,483
This is the hardest
   thing I've ever had
to do in my life.

196
00:18:41,787 --> 00:18:44,690
I'm filing for a divorce.
  Please try and understand.

197
00:18:46,859 --> 00:18:48,494
We have to get on
with our lives.

198
00:18:50,496 --> 00:18:52,764
Emma has to stop crying
  over her daddy every night

199
00:18:52,798 --> 00:18:54,533
and I need to stop
 crying over you too.

200
00:18:57,603 --> 00:18:58,670
I need you to understand.

201
00:19:01,974 --> 00:19:04,576
(WHISPERS) I'm sorry.

202
00:19:04,610 --> 00:19:06,712
Karen, please don't.
 Karen, wait.

203
00:19:06,745 --> 00:19:07,946
Please wait!

204
00:19:15,821 --> 00:19:17,289
(YELLS IN FRUSTRATION)

205
00:19:24,830 --> 00:19:26,632
(SIGHS)

206
00:19:26,665 --> 00:19:28,367
(SNIFFS)

207
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:29,635
(GROANS)

208
00:20:14,780 --> 00:20:16,248
(DOOR CLOSES)

209
00:20:17,649 --> 00:20:18,850
Mr. Preston,

210
00:20:23,522 --> 00:20:24,823
one bad apple,

211
00:20:26,058 --> 00:20:27,960
can spoil the whole bushel.

212
00:20:30,629 --> 00:20:31,797
My father told me that.

213
00:20:35,901 --> 00:20:37,669
If this country wants
  to be great again,

214
00:20:40,105 --> 00:20:41,640
if we want to save the...

215
00:20:42,941 --> 00:20:43,976
...whole bushel,

216
00:20:45,477 --> 00:20:46,812
(INHALES DEEPLY)

217
00:20:46,845 --> 00:20:49,715
then we need to find
   the rotten apples

218
00:20:51,350 --> 00:20:52,751
and destroy 'em.

219
00:20:54,686 --> 00:20:56,588
Before the rot spreads.

220
00:21:00,392 --> 00:21:03,028
That'll leave us with a clean,
 wholesome society.

221
00:21:05,931 --> 00:21:09,067
A new world order
  of perfect apples,

222
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:11,503
Mr. Preston.

223
00:21:14,406 --> 00:21:15,874
I'd like you
 to think about that.

224
00:21:19,111 --> 00:21:20,679
I'm gonna leave this
   right over here.

225
00:21:29,621 --> 00:21:31,757
I, uh,

226
00:21:31,790 --> 00:21:33,692
suspect you'll get hungry
  sooner or later.

227
00:21:59,551 --> 00:22:01,553
(ANNOUNCER SPEAKING ON PA)

228
00:22:17,736 --> 00:22:19,971
You knew the risks, Della.

229
00:22:20,005 --> 00:22:21,940
You hung me out there, Neil.

230
00:22:21,973 --> 00:22:24,509
You were hung out there
from the first.

231
00:22:24,543 --> 00:22:27,546
It was a sensitive operation.
 The political ones always are.

232
00:22:27,579 --> 00:22:29,147
I couldn't help you then.
  You were too hot.

233
00:22:29,181 --> 00:22:30,549
You abandoned me.

234
00:22:31,483 --> 00:22:33,018
Well, I am here.

235
00:22:33,051 --> 00:22:34,853
-And I can help you.
   -How?

236
00:22:34,886 --> 00:22:36,888
Can you give me
my family back?

237
00:22:36,922 --> 00:22:38,657
Can you return
   my daughter's birthdays?

238
00:22:38,690 --> 00:22:41,493
No, I can't give you any
   of those things,

239
00:22:41,526 --> 00:22:42,961
but I can give you
  a little something.

240
00:22:42,994 --> 00:22:45,163
And what exactly
 would that be, Neil?

241
00:22:45,197 --> 00:22:48,166
Your freedom.

242
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:51,970
Two agents have tried,
  but they've come up short.

243
00:22:52,003 --> 00:22:53,905
And worse than that,
 they've disappeared,

244
00:22:53,939 --> 00:22:56,174
but you, you're better
  than both of them.

245
00:22:56,208 --> 00:22:57,743
And you've got
   nothing to lose.

246
00:22:59,778 --> 00:23:01,146
So,

247
00:23:01,179 --> 00:23:03,215
I do one more job for you
  and what?

248
00:23:03,248 --> 00:23:04,883
I get a pardon?

249
00:23:04,916 --> 00:23:07,085
No, we were thinking more
  in the lines of an escape.

250
00:23:07,119 --> 00:23:10,188
(CHUCKLES HUMORLESSLY)
I don't think so, Neil.

251
00:23:10,222 --> 00:23:12,657
You think I wanna
  spend the rest of
  my life on the run?

252
00:23:12,691 --> 00:23:13,992
Oh, you wouldn't
be on the run.

