00:43:28,339 --> 00:43:29,340
Why?

495
00:43:29,373 --> 00:43:31,976
Mr. Sebastian, those young
men you just manhandled

496
00:43:32,009 --> 00:43:34,878
work for Arno Taylor
  at Freedom.

497
00:43:34,912 --> 00:43:38,082
Look, you haven't really
  broken any law here

498
00:43:38,115 --> 00:43:43,454
and I can't just tell you to
   get out of dodge, but
   they're a bad bunch,

499
00:43:43,487 --> 00:43:45,022
and you seem like a nice
   enough guy.

500
00:43:46,323 --> 00:43:48,459
Maybe you should reconsider.

501
00:43:48,492 --> 00:43:50,194
Is that official advice,
   Officer?

502
00:43:51,061 --> 00:43:53,364
Yes. Yes it is.

503
00:43:54,298 --> 00:43:56,300
-Then I will.
-Good.

504
00:43:58,268 --> 00:43:59,303
(ENGINE STARTS)

505
00:45:06,904 --> 00:45:09,206
(SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

506
00:45:09,239 --> 00:45:12,309
-Hey. Hey, look who's here.
-What is it?

507
00:45:12,342 --> 00:45:13,477
Sheep boy.

508
00:45:14,411 --> 00:45:16,113
Hey, look who's here.

509
00:45:29,393 --> 00:45:32,296
Come on, I don't want any
  more trouble. Haven't you
  guys had enough?

510
00:45:32,329 --> 00:45:34,531
You should've thought of that
  before you came in the yard.
   Sheep boy!

511
00:45:34,565 --> 00:45:35,399
(GRUNTS)

512
00:45:37,534 --> 00:45:39,536
Hey, hey! What is the matter
   with you, huh?

513
00:45:39,570 --> 00:45:41,038
Huh?
  What's the matter with you?

514
00:45:41,071 --> 00:45:42,005
You a slow learner?
  Is that what it is?

515
00:45:42,039 --> 00:45:43,173
Whoa, gentlemen!

516
00:45:45,042 --> 00:45:46,910
Who the hell are you?

517
00:45:46,944 --> 00:45:50,514
This boy right here, boss.
He just seems to wanna find
 trouble.

518
00:45:50,547 --> 00:45:54,151
Mr. Pete, please. I wasn't
 speaking to you.

519
00:45:54,184 --> 00:45:56,286
My name's Del Sebastian.

520
00:45:56,320 --> 00:45:58,455
What can I do for you,
Mr. Sebastian?

521
00:46:01,125 --> 00:46:02,392
I heard you were hiring.

522
00:46:04,595 --> 00:46:06,830
I might be.

523
00:46:06,864 --> 00:46:09,166
At least we should talk about
  the possibilities,

524
00:46:09,199 --> 00:46:11,101
before you do any more damage
  to my crew.

525
00:46:14,438 --> 00:46:15,873
(SIGHS)

526
00:46:15,906 --> 00:46:18,242
So, you're looking for work.

527
00:46:20,644 --> 00:46:24,448
Do you always present
   such an aggressive
   first impression?

528
00:46:24,481 --> 00:46:27,417
Well, I seem to lately,
Mr. Taylor,

529
00:46:27,451 --> 00:46:30,220
although I generally
   prefer to think
   through a problem

530
00:46:30,254 --> 00:46:32,556
before I'm forced
 to attack it.

531
00:46:32,589 --> 00:46:36,193
That's sound reasoning,
Mr. Sebastian.

532
00:46:36,226 --> 00:46:38,128
What kind of work
 are you looking for?

533
00:46:38,162 --> 00:46:42,499
Well, I'm licensed on most
 heavy equipment
 and demolitions.

534
00:46:42,533 --> 00:46:46,336
I can take orders
 and I know how to do my job.

535
00:46:46,370 --> 00:46:49,640
And I'll give you an honest
day's work for an honest
day's pay.

536
00:46:49,673 --> 00:46:52,042
Where'd you get
   your experience?

537
00:46:52,075 --> 00:46:56,246
Military mostly. First with
   the Army Corp Stateside,

538
00:46:56,280 --> 00:46:58,582
later as a ranger with the
 Third Battalion.

539
00:46:58,615 --> 00:47:00,350
I served in Vietnam.

540
00:47:00,384 --> 00:47:03,053
That would be where you got
 your expertise in demolitions?

541
00:47:03,086 --> 00:47:04,588
Mmm-hmm.

542
00:47:04,621 --> 00:47:06,890
-Where in 'Nam did you serve?
  -Mekong Delta.

543
00:47:08,659 --> 00:47:11,195
Well, your qualifications
  are adequate,

544
00:47:11,228 --> 00:47:15,265
and we can always use another
  hand in our modest effort

545
00:47:15,299 --> 00:47:18,468
to build a better America.

546
00:47:18,502 --> 00:47:23,207
Yeah, I was hired
this morning.
No, no problem at all.

547
00:47:23,240 --> 00:47:26,343
Right. I'll let you know what
 I find out as soon as I can.

548
00:47:26,376 --> 00:47:28,445
You do that,
 but remember,

549
00:47:28,478 --> 00:47:30,647
Taylor is very sharp.
 We need this,

550
00:47:30,681 --> 00:47:32,916
but you can't afford any more
  mistakes.

551
00:47:34,084 --> 00:47:35,085
(LINE DISCONNECTS)

552
00:47:35,118 --> 00:47:36,186
(BEEPING)

553
00:47:39,156 --> 00:47:42,192
(WHISTLES) Hey!

554
00:47:42,226 --> 00:47:44,461
Taylor wants you over at
   Springfield Bridge this
   afternoon.

555
00:47:44,494 --> 00:47:46,496
We're gonna blow some
 bedrock. You know how
 to get there?

556
00:47:46,530 --> 00:47:48,699
-I'll find it.
  -All right.

557
00:47:48,732 --> 00:47:51,468
Go see Walter
   over in building four
   and get some detonators.

558
00:47:51,501 --> 00:47:53,270
Get what you need and then
 get on over there.

559
00:47:55,672 --> 00:47:57,040
Right.

560
00:48:27,371 --> 00:48:28,705
(BIRD FLAPPING OVERHEAD)

561
00:49:00,037 --> 00:49:02,739
(BARKING)

562
00:49:08,512 --> 00:49:10,047
Nice doggy.

563
00:49:13,317 --> 00:49:15,452
(BARKING CONTINUES DISTANTLY)

564
00:49:31,134 --> 00:49:31,735
SEBASTIAN: Hello?

565
00:49:35,706 --> 00:49:36,506
Hello?

566
00:49:38,542 --> 00:49:39,576
Hello?

567
00:49:39,609 --> 00:49:41,411
Jesus Christ!

568
00:49:41,445 --> 00:49:42,746
-Okay...
-Who the hell are you?

569
00:49:42,779 --> 00:49:44,715
I didn't mean to scare you,
Walter.

570
00:49:44,748 --> 00:49:47,584
You know my name?
 Who the hell are you?

571
00:49:47,617 --> 00:49:48,819
Are you from
  the bowling alley?

572
00:49:48,852 --> 00:49:51,188
Bowling alley?

573
00:49:51,221 --> 00:49:52,656
Yeah, a pair of
   shoes are missing.
   They think I stole them.

574
00:49:52,689 --> 00:49:55,125
No, no. My name's Del.
   I'm the new guy.

575
00:49:55,158 --> 00:49:57,060
-Yeah.
-I'm looking for
building four.

576
00:49:57,761 --> 00:49:59,496
I need some detonators.

577
00:49:59,529 --> 00:50:02,532
-Oh, building four, right.
 -Right. Yeah.

578
00:50:02,566 --> 00:50:04,201
-You found it.
   -(LAUGHS) Right.

579
00:50:04,234 --> 00:50:06,536
-What do ya need?
   -I need some detonators.

580
00:50:06,570 --> 00:50:08,472
-Detonators. Not a problem.
-All right.

581
00:50:10,607 --> 00:50:12,142
I got what you need.
 Here you go.

582
00:50:14,511 --> 00:50:16,313
Got 'em.

583
00:50:16,346 --> 00:50:19,116
Actually, check this out.
  State of the art.

584
00:50:23,220 --> 00:50:25,322
Nice, huh?

585
00:50:25,355 --> 00:50:27,624
Top quality.
 You know explosives?

586
00:50:27,657 --> 00:50:29,292
-Beautiful.
   -Yeah, beautiful.

587
00:50:29,326 --> 00:50:32,129
But we won't waste those
on the Springfield job now,
will we?

588
00:50:32,162 --> 00:50:33,430
-No.
   -Mmm-mmm.

589
00:50:35,365 --> 00:50:36,600
I got what you need.

590
00:50:39,202 --> 00:50:40,670
Yeah, take some of these.
  You'll need some of those.

591
00:50:41,872 --> 00:50:43,707
Hey, hey, hey, hey,
hey, hey, hey!

592
00:50:43,740 --> 00:50:45,442
(CLATTERING)

593
00:50:45,475 --> 00:50:47,811
Del, Del.
Ever see one of these?

594
00:50:48,678 --> 00:50:49,780
Can't say as I have.

595
00:50:49,813 --> 00:50:51,381
It's a dead man's wheel.

596
00:50:54,184 --> 00:50:58,455
The old time
explosive guys used these.
Remember dynamite, Del?

597
00:50:58,488 --> 00:51:02,159
They just dial in the job,
 big building, little building,

598
00:51:02,192 --> 00:51:06,430
small hole, big hole,
  tree stumps, boulders,
  outhouses. (LAUGHS)

599
00:51:06,463 --> 00:51:08,532
-Whatever. Dead man's wheel.
   -Right.

600
00:51:09,900 --> 00:51:13,303
So, why do they call it
  a dead man's wheel?

601
00:51:13,336 --> 00:51:16,206
Oh. 'Cause they weren't always
 accurate, Del.

602
00:51:16,239 --> 00:51:17,140
(LAUGHS MANIACALLY)

603
00:51:19,876 --> 00:51:22,679
-What's in here, Walt?
 -No, no, no, no, no,
 no, no, no.

604
00:51:22,712 --> 00:51:26,416
"Authorized personnel only.
Keep out."

605
00:51:26,450 --> 00:51:28,485
This means Y-O-U.

606
00:51:28,518 --> 00:51:32,422
I'm the only one with the key.
 Not supposed to let anybody
 in here.

607
00:51:32,456 --> 00:51:33,323
-You wanna see?
   -Love to.

608
00:51:33,356 --> 00:51:34,825
(LAUGHS) Okay.

609
00:51:34,858 --> 00:51:36,259
(CLATTERING)

610
00:51:39,362 --> 00:51:40,764
(DOOR UNLOCKING)

611
00:51:45,602 --> 00:51:47,204
(WHISPERS) Be quiet,
 quiet, quiet.

612
00:51:52,442 --> 00:51:54,611
-(WHISTLES)
-Yeah. (LAUGHS)

613
00:51:54,644 --> 00:51:56,513
It's something else,
   isn't it?

614
00:51:56,546 --> 00:51:59,583
-Definitely top shelf, Walt.
   -You betcha.

615
00:51:59,616 --> 00:52:02,953
Mr. Taylor only gets
the best stuff.

616
00:52:02,986 --> 00:52:05,856
Yeah. This is only one of my
   buildings. I got four.

617
00:52:05,889 --> 00:52:07,090
Yeah.

618
00:52:07,124 --> 00:52:10,794
A lot of this stuff is going
 out of here tomorrow. Big job.

619
00:52:10,827 --> 00:52:13,296
SEBASTIAN: Yeah, I think
   Mr. Taylor actually
   mentioned it.

620
00:52:13,330 --> 00:52:15,398
Where was that again?

621
00:52:15,432 --> 00:52:18,335
WALTER: I don't know.
   The Inquisition
   doesn't tell me.

622
00:52:18,368 --> 00:52:19,870
I think it's in Washington.

623
00:52:19,903 --> 00:52:21,838
Yeah.

624
00:52:21,872 --> 00:52:24,941
-Big bang stuff here, Walter.
  -Oh, yeah.

625
00:52:24,975 --> 00:52:28,411
Yeah. Big, big bang stuff
  here.

626
00:52:28,445 --> 00:52:30,614
Want a cigarette?

627
00:52:30,647 --> 00:52:33,517
You know,
 I think I'm going to
 pass on that.

628
00:52:33,550 --> 00:52:35,285
But thanks for your help.
I gotta get these back.

629
00:52:35,318 --> 00:52:36,520
Suit yourself.

630
00:52:39,990 --> 00:52:41,224
Come on.

631
00:52:56,339 --> 00:52:57,841
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

632
00:52:57,874 --> 00:52:59,409
(ENGINE STARTS)

633
00:53:10,320 --> 00:53:11,655
(ENGINE STARTS)

634
00:54:03,006 --> 00:54:06,843
Well, Mr. Sebastian.
 Planning a trip with the boss?

635
00:54:06,876 --> 00:54:09,779
What's going on?

636
00:54:09,813 --> 00:54:11,381
Isn't that
  Freedom Corporation's
  hangar down there?

637
00:54:11,414 --> 00:54:13,316
It is indeed.

638
00:54:13,350 --> 00:54:14,751
So what are you doing up here?

639
00:54:14,784 --> 00:54:16,853
Today's my day
  to play guard dog.

640
00:54:16,886 --> 00:54:19,522
-For Arno Taylor?
  -Who else?

641
00:54:19,556 --> 00:54:21,758
-Why?
-Well, he asked me to.

642
00:54:21,791 --> 00:54:25,729
Apparently, one of his
 disgruntled clients
 is a bit of a wacko,

643
00:54:25,762 --> 00:54:27,831
so he wanted me to follow him
  up here just in case
  the guy shows.

644
00:54:27,864 --> 00:54:29,065
(LAUGHS) You're kidding.

645
00:54:29,099 --> 00:54:30,800
Sounds a bit paranoid, huh?

646
00:54:30,834 --> 00:54:32,702
But it's tough to say no
   to the boss.

647
00:54:32,736 --> 00:54:35,538
Well, why didn't he
 just call us?

648
00:54:35,572 --> 00:54:39,843
Well, that had something to do
 with cops in skirts that
 didn't instill confidence.

649
00:54:39,876 --> 00:54:42,579
-His words, not mine.
  -Okay.

650
00:54:42,612 --> 00:54:45,849
So, um, I was kinda
 wondering...

651
00:54:47,083 --> 00:54:48,418
Yeah?

652
00:54:48,451 --> 00:54:50,453
What does one do for fun in
this town?

653
00:54:50,487 --> 00:54:51,655
Hmm...

654
00:54:52,088 --> 00:54:53,857
(CLICKS TONGUE)

655
00:54:53,890 --> 00:54:55,358
Do you bowl?

656
00:54:55,392 --> 00:55:00,130
Bowl? Big ball? Heavy?
  That? Not recently.

657
00:55:00,163 --> 00:55:01,965
Well, that's about it.

658
00:55:01,998 --> 00:55:04,834
I see. Well, in that case,
 Officer Cole,

659
00:55:04,868 --> 00:55:06,503
would you like to go
   bowling with me tonight?

660
00:55:08,071 --> 00:55:10,874
Sure. As long as I can pay my
  own way.

661
00:55:10,907 --> 00:55:13,143
No problem. In fact,
I'll do you one better.

662
00:55:13,176 --> 00:55:14,477
You can pay my way as well.

663
00:55:14,511 --> 00:55:16,680
(LAUGHING) Okay, deal.

664
00:55:18,982 --> 00:55:21,618
Uh... I gotta go.
My boy is on the move.

665
00:55:21,651 --> 00:55:23,053
-I'll see you tonight.
-Looking forward to it.

666
00:55:23,086 --> 00:55:24,954
-Around 8:00.
-Okay.

667
00:55:24,988 --> 00:55:26,089
(ENGINE STARTS)

668
00:57:39,189 --> 00:57:41,858
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

669
00:59:55,925 --> 00:59:56,926
Sebastian Dellacourt.

670
00:59:59,762 --> 01:00:00,930
Jesus.

671
01:00:01,965 --> 01:00:02,999
(MUMBLES)

672
01:00:04,233 --> 01:00:05,735
(DOOR OPENING)

673
01:00:16,179 --> 01:00:17,246
Fugitive.

674
01:00:22,719 --> 01:00:24,087
Oh, my God.

675
01:00:38,434 --> 01:00:40,269
Check the entire facility.

676
01:01:02,025 --> 01:01:04,961
Well, well.
  You're resourceful.

677
01:01:07,497 --> 01:01:10,366
Perhaps even more resourceful
  than we ever thought.

678
01:01:54,110 --> 01:01:55,878
(MACHINE HUMMING SOFTLY)

679
01:02:12,361 --> 01:02:13,396
(SHOUTING)

680
01:02:52,869 --> 01:02:53,970
(PHONE RINGING)

681
01:02:55,037 --> 01:02:56,139
County Sheriff's office.

682
01:02:57,039 --> 01:02:58,407
What?

683
01:02:58,441 --> 01:03:00,143
(PHONE RINGING)

684
01:03:03,646 --> 01:03:05,581
MALE OPERATOR:
   Capital Florists.

685
01:03:05,615 --> 01:03:07,283
SEBASTIAN: 
Stratton Records,
  please.

686
01:03:07,316 --> 01:03:08,851
OPERATOR: 
One moment
 while I transfer you.

687
01:03:08,885 --> 01:03:10,219
(PHONE RINGING)

688
01:03:11,654 --> 01:03:13,122
Stratton records.

689
01:03:13,156 --> 01:03:14,524
SEBASTIAN: 
Martha.

690
01:03:14,557 --> 01:03:17,160
Yeah, this is Martha Stratton.
 Can I help you?

691
01:03:17,193 --> 01:03:20,062
-Martha, it's Sebastian.
   -Sebastian?

692
01:03:20,096 --> 01:03:21,597
Sebastian Dellacourt?

693
01:03:21,631 --> 01:03:25,868
(LAUGHS) Exactly how many fans
 named Sebastian do you have?

694
01:03:25,902 --> 01:03:29,238
MARTHA: 
Only one, hon.
Jeez, I can't believe
it's you.

695
01:03:29,272 --> 01:03:32,308
I thought you were...
Well, it's great to
hear you voice.

696
01:03:32,341 --> 01:03:34,577
What can I do to help you,
 Sebastian?

697
01:03:34,610 --> 01:03:38,247
I... I need access to a file.
  Something Neil Kennedy's
  working on.

698
01:03:38,281 --> 01:03:39,515
(SIRENS BLARING)

699
01:03:39,549 --> 01:03:41,250
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

700
01:03:44,954 --> 01:03:45,555
(ENGINE STOPS)

701
01:03:47,156 --> 01:03:49,192
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

702
01:03:52,094 --> 01:03:53,296
(SIGHS)

703
01:04:03,372 --> 01:04:06,075
(PHONE RINGING)

704
01:04:06,108 --> 01:04:10,179
-Martha.
  -Very fruitful, but very
  strange, Sebastian.

705
01:04:10,213 --> 01:04:13,216
-How so?
  -Best I can tell from a quick
  glance is

706
01:04:13,249 --> 01:04:17,386
your Freedom Corporation
 is a front for a very
 active militia group,

707
01:04:17,420 --> 01:04:20,656
headed up by one Arno Taylor.

708
01:04:20,690 --> 01:04:23,492
-Hard, right-wing politics.
-(TYPING)

709
01:04:23,526 --> 01:04:26,596
These guys are not the type
to let their votes
do the talking.

710
01:04:26,629 --> 01:04:29,365
Lots of direct
political connections.

711
01:04:29,398 --> 01:04:33,302
Looks like Ambassador
Enrique Ramirez

712
01:04:33,336 --> 01:04:35,371
was one
  of many strong supporters.

713
01:04:35,404 --> 01:04:37,607
Ramirez?

714
01:04:37,640 --> 01:04:40,643
MARTHA: Yup. Seems Ramirez
   provided some very outspoken
   support

715
01:04:40,676 --> 01:04:43,379
for the kind of conservative
   agenda these guys like.

716
01:04:44,213 --> 01:04:46,582
Huh.

717
01:04:46,616 --> 01:04:50,453
It's possible he had some
 first-hand contact with the
 infamous Arno Taylor himself.

718
01:04:50,486 --> 01:04:52,655
There's a surveillance
 photo in here

719
01:04:52,688 --> 01:04:56,993
ID'ed as Taylor Santiago.

720
01:04:57,026 --> 01:05:00,229
It's dated the day before
   Ramirez was assassinated.

721
01:05:00,263 --> 01:05:02,331
What about Neil, Martha?

722
01:05:02,365 --> 01:05:07,436
Well, like I said, he's been
  cheek to jowl with this bunch
for a long time.

723
01:05:07,470 --> 01:05:09,138
Could be he was just
 keeping tabs on 'em.

724
01:05:10,640 --> 01:05:13,542
Nothing beyond that,
  Sebastian.

725
01:05:13,576 --> 01:05:17,179
Lots of dates, places,
 descriptions.

726
01:05:17,213 --> 01:05:20,383
But all is one step removed
from Neil.

727
01:05:20,416 --> 01:05:22,752
What's going on, Sebastian?

728
01:05:22,785 --> 01:05:26,322
I don't have any idea,
   although the plot definitely
   thickens.

729
01:06:04,493 --> 01:06:05,628
(GRUNTING)

730
01:06:25,748 --> 01:06:29,485
Mr. Dellacourt, I've been
  expecting you.

731
01:06:29,518 --> 01:06:32,188
Did you kill both of
my men outside?

732
01:06:32,221 --> 01:06:36,425
No. But one of them won't be
   spouting any more political
   rhetoric for a while.

733
01:06:36,459 --> 01:06:38,594
The incident at your house.

734
01:06:38,627 --> 01:06:40,463
It was just to
  get your attention.

735
01:06:40,496 --> 01:06:42,164
